node.text:
Finished in 1903, this home took 5 years to build.

Some materials were harvested on site and the rest was brought in from over 50 miles away, one wagon cart at a time on a primitive mountain turnpike

The large home also included boarding rooms for hunters who would come to the area seasonally.

#greatsmokymountainsnationalpark #gsmnp #thisoldhouse #oldhouselove #southernliving #historichomes #oldhouselovers

node.title: 1903 home in the mountains is a time capsule

node.text:
James built this house around 1890 where he lived with his first wife, Gerushia. They had 10 children together.

After she passed away in 1903, James married again, this time to Lillie. They would have 3 children, one of whom, also named Lillie, lived here through the 1960s.

Upon her death, she willed the property to the adjacent church and it appears they currently use it for storage.

Although it's missing it's porch, windows, doors and many of it's interior walls, it's charm and elegance are still apparent.

Besides the chairs you see pictured, all you'll find here is a committee of vultures.

node.text:
This c. 1850s home is slated for burning for training maneuvers by the local fire department in Edgecombe County, NC.

If you would like to voice your concerns about the proposed burning of this historic home, I encourage you to make a phone call to Eric Evans, Edgecombe County Manager at 252-641-7834.

Please call that office and (respectfully) register your objection to the planned burning of this house. if they hear from enough of us, maybe something can still be done. You can mention the 1850s home on Bulluck School Road outside Rocky Mount.

Today, this old church leans closer and closer to her demise, but at one point, it sat at the center of a Mississippi town, bustling with traffic from the river.

Not much of it remains today so I gathered as many old photos and tales of it as I could find to help tell the story of what happened to this place.

Check it out at the link in my stories or here on my website: theforgottensouth.com/rodney-mississippi-ghost-town-history-tour/

node.text:
As I pulled up to this house, the owner came from around the corner and gladly introduced himself.

He was working hard at clearing years of overgrowth from the surrounding land and explained that he would be completely renovating the old farmhouse, which had been empty for decades.

He graciously allowed me to tour the entire property so I could see for myself the magnificent construction and carpentry.

Somewhere along a quiet rural road in Alabama stands this old Presbyterian Church.

Not much is known about its early history but it’s especially striking because at some point, it was likely the center of a small community, that has all but vanished. It stands in a field with a gentle slope that was surrounded in pine trees until a clearing was done about 5 years ago.

A colony of bats has taken residence.🦇 There is no graveyard, no placquard, or sign. Nothing to tell us who built this place and when.

Research online and with local contacts hasn’t provided much information about its early history either, but I did find out that it was acquired in the early 2000s by the county historical society who had intentions to relocate and restore it in a nearby town, although I’m not sure what happened with that project.

Sometime in the past 5 years, the University of West Alabama took over ownership, also with intentions to fix it up. The original windows were removed and taken to their campus for safe-keeping until the project could begin. I haven’t been able to find any recent info on the project but I’ll update this post if I do.
